Using Amazon Rekognition to understand the potential biases of Machine Learning in Law Enforcement¶

Sofia Benzi, Marawan Elghory, Nati Marcus, Emily Shen, Kunal Suri, Haniel Paulos

With the increased use of facial recognition and ML in Law Enforcement, understanding the biases that this software has and how it groups individuals by specific facial features can help us understand potential pitfalls of discriminatory or disproportionate law enforcement against specific marginalized groups. In this post, we hope to show whether or not Amazon Rekognition’s “compare faces” feature tends to have higher error rates with certain features and manipulations, describe the data collection and analyzation processes, and discuss why this may be problematic in real-world application as well as offer some potential solutions.

Amazon Rekognition and Discrimination¶

According to this article from the ACLU, Amazon met up with ICE to discuss using Amazon Rekognition to “supercharge” deportation measures delegated by the Trump Administration. If Amazon Rekognition does, indeed, host biases against marginalized groups, a lot of people could be at risk for deportation or wrongful detention and apprehension. According to the ACLU:

In July, we released a test showing that Amazon Rekognition falsely matched 28 members of Congress with mugshot photos, with members of color incorrectly matched at a disproportionately higher rate.

These errors in Amazon Rekognition’s software and clear discriminatory biases could be disastrous for immigrants, communities of color, and protestors if implemented broadly.

The Goal¶

To test our hypothesis that Amazon Rekognition is not free from discriminatory bias, we plan to manipulate a single image variable to test the response of the ML service’s “Detect Faces” feature across multiple images of a diverse group of people. We will supply one copy of each photo as it is and use an altered version of that same photo to see how confidently the ML service can match the images and recongize the gender, emotion, and age range. During the initial stages of this project, we plan to host a few experiments by separately manipulating variables to decide which will be the best to use on a mass scale. Some manipulations we are considering making to the photos are changing the lighting and filters over the images or to mask parts of the face. Some questions we want to answer with our data analyzation include:

  • How does the confidence score of gender change when we apply a filter/mask a facial feature on the original image?

  • How does the the confisence of the age range change when we apply a filter/mask a facial feature on the original image?

  • Does the confidence score of the Major Emotion Type change when we apply a filter/mask a facial feature on the original image?

  • Grouping these images by a binary variable of "white" or "non-white" relating to race, does the confidence of these three variables change from one group to another after blurring these images?

Architecture¶

The Data Collection Process¶

Collection of portraits from an API¶

To gather the images we used in this study, we relied on images of portraits supplied by an API. We want to test pictures of males and females in the same ethnic group and age range to minimize the confounding variables. We used about 150 pictures generated from the public API. The public API we’ve decided to go with is unsplash.com, which is a picture database that contains over 50k photos under the keyword “portrait.” Here is an example image of some of the portraits available to us through this API.

As seen through these images, there is a wide variety of ages, genders, ethnic groups, photo conditions, and emotions that we can see through these images. This allows us to have a large and varied sample size for our testing. The advantage of the API is the large amount of portraits available lets us pick and choose based on what variables we want to test, lowering the risk of confounding variables. If it is feasible, we could go further and test hundreds of pictures to improve the generalizability of our result. This allows us to find even more intricate details hidden in Rekognition’s software and allows us to see if there is any possible issues with bias. Our foremost goal is to extend our test variables to age range and ethnic groups and measure those effects on emotional accuracy.

As seen here, Amazon prides itself on being accurate on these categories that we’re looking to test. Our goal is simply to measure the extent to which these claims are accurate, as, if Amazon is looking to implement this technology into Law enforcement, the margin of error should be minimal to avoid discrimination, stereotyping, or profiling.

Image Manipulation and Storage¶

In order to get the images necessary, we first created an Unsplash developers account to get an API key, and then used that key in order to request a .json with the following characteristics:

Query = portrait Per_page = 50 Page = 1-6 (required a separate API call for each page) Client_id = APIKEY (APIKEY is the variable we used to hide our API key)

This gave us 180 total images to use in our analysis, 30 per API call, and allowed us to have plenty of data points. Unfortunately, we had to remove a few of the images from our analysis, due to their size being too big to fit into Rekognition or containing multiple faces which would complicate our analysis. Since Unsplash delivers images through a .json with multiple URLs, we chose to filter the .json’s results to the regular size images using the jq package from bash.

We named each image portrait_”#”.jpg where the # would correspond to a new number labelled from 1-180 to correspond to the order in which it was downloaded. Afterwards, we used the Image and ImageFilter classes from the Pillow package to take our original images and create blurred copies of them for our analysis using the GaussianFilter method. Finally, we used the shutil class in order to move our .jpegs into their respective folders within our google drive.

Here is an example of an image we blurred (portrait 1):

Data Frames and Variable Manipulation¶

Our Data Collection team first uploaded about 175 images to a GitHub Repo for our team to easily access. Two groups of the same 175 images were uploaded, but one of the sets had the blurred filter applied across all images.

To create the dataframes for use, The first step was to create s3 buckets for the original portraits and the blurred portraits and to upload the pictures into these buckets.

We then created a list that created the filenames for each of the photos and used them in a loop to get the ‘FaceDetails’ data from each photo after it was run through Rekognition.

We then created a list that contained a list of various attributes for each photo (filename, lowest age guess, highest age guess, gender, gender confidence score, top emotion, top emotion confidence score)

After gathering this info we compiled it into a dataframe for all of the non-blurred photos, and then repeated the process for all of the blurred photos to create a second dataframe. We then joined these dataframes by row.

The reason we created this ultimate dataframe was because we decided it would be easiest to run an analysis on a dataframe containing the attributes that we sought to study, and combining them together would keep this analysis more organized.

Some problems we ran into during this process included the following:

  • By increasing sample size of images, some of the files were too large to be analyzed by Rekognition. Another member of our Data Collection team then compressed the photos and they were re-uploaded to the s3 buckets and run through Rekognition successfully.
  • After creating the initial dataframe, we noticed that the size of the dataframe was larger than the sample size, so we checked and found that certain images had multiple faces within the image. These images were then excluded from analysis and left out of future iterations of the dataframe.
  • After removing the problematic images from the dataframe, the numbering of the files was inaccurate. So, we corrected the code that assigned the filename when pulling other attributes.

As a visualization of or two initial dataframe structures, below is a glimpse of the original images and the data we first pulled from Rekognition.

Here is a glimpse of the data frame we then attached to the prior, of the blurred images.

Data Metrics¶

To measure our three variables of interest; gender, emotion, and age range, we used Rekognition's confidence score of these three variables from the images we uploaded, both blurred and original, to measure the difference of the confidence scores on each altered image. Using these numbers, we can determine if Rekognition has a harder time telling the binary gender, emotion, and continuous age range of the faces in images that have been blurred. We hypothesize that indeed, Rekognition will have lower confidence in these variables for the blurred images.

To see if there is in fact a bias in these measurements across race, we constructed and manually entered a binary variable for each image: "white" and "non-white". In our analysis, we look at the confidence scores between these groups to see if there is a bias in Rekognition. We hypothesize all three variables will have higher confidence scores for the white group than the non-white group.

Finally, after our analysis, we looked at the inconsistency of AWS' predicitions for each metric.

With supervised ML models, an important metric that pops up is accuracy. With labeled data, ML models usually are trained to reduce the misclassification error. As the images are blurred, details are lost in the picture so it is worth looking at whether the ML model reproduces the same labels. So we will look at consistency as an evaluation metric.

Inconsistency = k images / n images where k is # of images that have different labels for a given feature before and after blurring and n = # of total images

Here is a summary of those inconsistencies:

  • There were 10 changes in gender labeling. The inconsistency rate between gender predictions is 0.057. The inconsistency rate is only 5.7%, which is not a huge impact.

  • The inconsistency rate between lowAge labels using typical survey ranges is 0.24 The inconsistency rate between highAge labels using typical survey ranges is 0.263 This is based off of hypothetical age range labels. Typically, we would see these kind of ranges or stages of life: child, young adult, adult, elderly, etc.

  • There were 5 changes in emotion labeling. The inconsistency rate between emotion predictions is 0.029. After blurring, we observed that AWS changes its emotion labeling on five people with the inconsistency rate of 2.9%. Among the five changes, three of them are from SAD to CALM, and one is from FEAR to DISGUESTED. These emotions all have similar facial expressions. Even a real human being may not be able to easily distinguish between them. Therefore, we could say that blurring only slightly hinders the machine's ability to detect emotions.

Variable 1: Gender Confidence Score¶

Gender here is defined by a categorical variable, "male" or "female". We can see above there are 2 columns with the predicted gender and 2 columns with the respective confidence score output by Rekognition. The first column is associated with the original images and the second is associated with the blurred images. We hypothesize that the confidence score of the predicted gender will be reduced with the blurred filter.

However, in reality, we saw that the mean confidence in the gender predicted increases after the image is blurred. This was an interesting result as it went against what we thought. Since some details are lost after blurring an image, we expected AWS Rekognition to exhbit less confidence in it's gender prediction.

We see that the standard deviation in gender confidence does increase after blurring. This may mean that the confidence varies more after blurring. This suggests that for most pictures that already have high confidence in gender score predictions, blurring helps remove details that reduce confidence in the pre-blur gender prediction. Pictures that had low gender confidence scores will result in even lower scores after blurring the image.

Distribution of Gender Confidence¶

The mean for predicted gender confidence is 92.503 before blurring and is 93.998 after blurring. The change in the mean was +1.5 (1.616%)

The std for predicted gender confidence is 12.473 before blurring and is 10.659 after blurring. The change in the std was -1.81 (-14.543%)

Having seen this distribution, we then took a look at how many males and females AWS Rekognition predicted were in the dataset before and after blurring the images. The following is the output of our code:

Before blur, AWS Rekognition predicted there are 64 males and 111 females in our dataset.

After blur, AWS Rekognition predicted there are 56 males and 119 females in our dataset.

After blurring, AWS identifies more females than before. This makes sense as males have sharper facial features, and blurring the image would soften edges on male faces. Therefore, the machine would miscalculate some males as females after blurring.

Hypothesis Testing¶

To further examine the difference between the distribution of the two groups, we computed a 95% confidence interval for their means, assuming a normal distribution. Our sample size is only 100+, which is not large enough, so we choose to use T-tests. T-tests are most useful when we need to determine if there is a statistically significant difference between two independent sample groups.

In [27]:
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
print('The 95% confidence interval for the gender of the images before blurring is:', sms.DescrStatsW(dataframe['genderConfidence']).tconfint_mean())

The 95% confidence interval for the gender of the images before blurring is: (90.64237472842234, 94.36413955729194)
In [29]:

The 95% confidence interval for the gender of the images after blurring is: (92.4078465257092, 95.58849633143365)

Regression Analysis¶

We posed a question before conducting the regression analysis - if we know a picture's gender confidence score in AWS, what will be its gender confidence score after we apply the blurring filter? Will it increase or decrease?

Our hypothesis is that blurring the image would lower its gender confidence score in AWS. We want to use regression analysis to answer this question.

In the following analysis, we included all pictures, and we tested the relationship between the gender confidence score before blurring and the gender confidence score after blurring.

In [50]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as smf
results_g = smf.ols('b_genderConf~genderConfidence ', data=dataframe).fit()
results_g.params

plt.plot(dataframe['genderConfidence'], results_g.predict(dataframe['genderConfidence']))
Out[51]:

Gender Confidence Score Analysis and Results¶

As can be observed from the plot, we discovered a positive relationship between the gender confidence score before blurring and the gender confidence score after blurring. We have a regression slope of +0.507. A positive coefficient indicates that a picture's gender confidence score in AWS will increase after we apply the blurring filter. Considering the range of confidence score before blurring is 100 and after blurring is also 100, +0.507 is a fairly small impact. However, this was still a surprising finding, because we expected the blurring filter to hinder the machine's ability to detect one's gender and to lower the gender confidence score. However, through our analysis, we found that blurring the images actually slightly improved the machine's confidence score about gender detection. Our guess is that AWS Rekognition over simplifies some facial features when it is calculating the gender. When we blurred the images, some facial details were lost, which made it easier for the machine to simplify the facial features and thus improved its confidence score.

Variable 2: Age Range¶

Looking at the first 6 rows of the dataframe, we see that Rekognition predicts a high age and a low age to form an age range for each image and a confidence score that the age of the person in the photo is between those two numbers. To minimize confusion, the data analysis team found the mean age for each image and added a column to the dataframe. For this variable, we again hypothesize that the confidence scores of the age range will be reduced with the blurred filter applied to the images.

Looking at the ageLow and ageHigh predicted by Rekognition, we found that the mean age decreased for both variables after images were blurred. The standard deviation also decreases for both variables meaning that the distribution of ages predicted is more similar. This makes sense as the ML model may process wrinkles and that is softened by blur effects.

In the visualization, we can also see the left tail of low age shifts to the right after blurring suggesting people who look younger before the blur also now look a bit older to the model.

Variable 3: Emotion¶

In the dataframe used for this study, the emotion is listed as a categorical variable and AWS Rekognition's confidence score that the emotion corresponding with the image is in fact the emotion seen in the picture.

We hypothesize AWS Rekognition will exhbit less confidence in its emotion recognition and more variations in the emotion confidence scores since detail is lost after blurring.

Now, we would like to use a histogram to show the distribution of the emotion confidence score before and after we blur the pictures.

The mean for predicted emotion confidence is 82.092 before blurring and is 83.783 after blurring. The change in the mean was +1.69 (2.06%)

The std for predicted emotion confidence is 18.38 before blurring and is 17.581 after blurring. The change in the std was -0.8 (-4.347%)

Above we see that the mean confidence in the emotion predicted increases 1.7 units after the image is blurred. We also see that the standard deviation in gender confidence scores decreases after blurring. This means that the emotion confidence score varies less after blurring. These are interesting results as they oppose our hypothesis.

Using this Information to Explore Potential Racial Biases in These Results¶

By grouping our data into "white" and "non white", we can explore how these confidence scores change with the implementation of a blurred filter over top in each group and if one group has a higher general confidence score than the other.

We hypothesize that both before and after blurring the images, the "white" group will have higher confidence scores for each variable than the "nonwhite" group. We assume the testing dataset was more heavily comprised of white people than not, and will therefore have higher accuracy with these images.

Let's take a look of the structure of the dataset. Recall these values were entered manually.

Results¶

As we observe from the results, no matter whether we have a blurred image or not, the mean age for the white group is higher than the mean age of the non-white group. Moreover, the standard deviation of scores for the non-white group is lower than it is for the white group. However, the difference in mean and standard deviation between the white and non-white groups are both small. For mean, the difference is about one unit in both normal and blurred cases. For the std, there appears to be more deviation.

This tells us that even though the machine is slightly more confident and consistent in predicting the age of the non-white group, it doesn’t really have a bias towards the white group.

Overall, the machine assumes the white group to be older than the non-white group, a very fascinating result.

Results¶

Above, we see the mean confidence score for emotion before blurring the images is higher among the non-white group than the white group, and the standard deviation is lower. The difference in these means is less than 2.0, and the difference in stds is less than 1.0, indicating little effect. After blurring the images, the means of the confidence scores in emotion is much closer between the two groups, and the std is still less than 1.0. Again, we can not explicity say that race has a strong effect on the confidence score Rekognition outputs regarding emotion.

Conclusions¶

Overall, this study taught us a lot about Amazon Rekognition's capabilities in dealing with altered and imperfect images.

When looking at gender before and after blurring the images, we actually find that the confidence score improves; countering our hypothesis.

When looking at age before and after the blurring the images, we do in fact see a slight decrease in the machine's confidence, as we had suspected.

When looking at the emotion before and after blurring the images, we again see a slightly improved confidence score, again countering our hypothesis.

As for combining these variables with race, we found the following:

The output of the machine's confidence in age with the implementation of a blurred filter across racial groups are slightly volatile, but do not point to any bias.

The output of the machine's confidence in gender with the implementation of a blurred filter across racial groups are slightly more confident and consistent with the white group, but not enough to consider discriminatory.

The output of the machine's confidence in emotion with the implementation of a blurred filter does not claim bias.

Amazon Rekognition proved its abilities in this study and was not found to host significant racial bias. This is promising news, but needs further development to insure that it truly is appropriate for ICE's needs before being implemented in such a serious manner.
